d at a high inclination angle and\nhosts a typical NS with a mass of 1.3 \\pm 0.3 Msun. At the moment, the large\nuncertainty on the radio position of this millisecond pulsar prevents us from\nrobustly concluding that the detected star is its optical counterpart.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 8 Mar 2019 10:02:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-17"}
